Hornets is land based in our three shops in the heart of Kensington, what we post on Instagram is a very small taster of the very large and varied stock we carry in the shops, and new stock goes in every day.
Importantly we are a long established business that is open seven days a week, 11 to 6.

Rudolf Beaufays R.I.P

Rudolf founder of the famous men’s vintage shop in Hamburg that bears his name, was a big handsome imposing man, sophisticated and cultured with great style and taste, he stood out, he was good company if he liked you, though a lot of the time he didn’t bother, we always got along very well, there was a mutual professional and personal respect.
When Rudolf came to London on buying trips he always made Hornets his base, every day after a couple of whisky’s, he always carried a large bottle in his bag, we’d have a long late lunch at my friend Romano’s restaurant, Rudolf and I would eat, drink and talk the afternoon away, early evening after Romano reopened I’d put Rudolf in a taxi to his hotel, this would go on for two or three days.
Some time ago, Meisun Ferhat took over the shop in Hamburg, flying the flag of Rudolf’s style with her own.

I miss you, Rudolf, you were in many ways unique.
Bill Hornets.

Harry Belafonte. R.I.P.
1927-2023. (aged 96)
Singer, Actor, Activist.
His album Calypso became the first LP in the world to sell more than 1 million copies within a year.
He had both critical and financial success with his films.
He was a close confidant of Martin Luther King Jr. during the Civil Rights Movement.
His mentor was the actor, singer and activist Paul Robeson.
He received many Honours and won many awards.

In the 50’s everything in the Man’s Shop was made in Britain by established names.

The Nutters Look.
When Tommy Nutter of Savile Row opened in 1969 with bold and original window displays, Tommy’s wide lapels, flairs, bold colours and checks, and Edward Sexton’s brilliant cutting and tailoring the ‘Seventies’ and it’s look were about to arrive. The Beatles ( the suits on the famous album cover Abbey Road) Mick and Bianca Jagger and a host of other stars and names poured through the doors. Quote from Edward Sexton ‘ I didn’t know most of the celebrities Tommy brought he promised the world, then I had to deliver it’. Peter Brown and Cilla Black were the principal backers ( the money), Brown and Tommy both with good looks, charm and personality were a team of two, Brown had been Brian Epsteins right hand and was the Beatles manager.
Edward Sexton bought Tommy out of Nutters of Savile Row and eventually Tommy opened again as Nutters Savile Row, with a ready to wear collection and bespoke he was one of the first menswear fashion designers and famously designed Jack Nicholsons costumes for the Joker in the Batman film.
Tommy tragically died of aids (the disease that wiped out so much creative talent)in 1992, Edward Sexton having been back in Savile Row for over a year, died this year, but his team are still there carrying on the Sexton tradition of excellent cutting and tailoring, Peter Brown who has had great success in music management and PR is still in New York, which has been his base for over forty years ( he’s a bit of a legend too), he co-wrote a book on the Beatles, maybe he’ll write about Tommy Nutter, or maybe some writer will do an in-depth interview with him about those heady times with Tommy and the beginning of Nutters
and he’ll tell all, better hurry writer he’s the only one left alive.

A Black Label  Burton, the tailor that brought style and good tailoring to the High Street, and became Sir Montague.
Londoners coined the phrase ‘The Full Monty’ when Montague was selling in the street market where he started, they could get a three piece suit and a shirt at a very good price, the Full Outfit, then with a pair of new boots they were fitted out for that big Saturday night out or their wedding at a Register Office, then a ‘booze up’ in the pub.
Sir Monty is part of U.K tailoring history.

THE TRILBY HAT.
The hat’s name is derived from the stage production of George Du Maurier’s 1894 novel‘Trilby’ set among bohemian types in Paris on the left bank of the Siene. The titular character is a young singer manipulated by a wicked showbiz manager named Svengali (Du Maurier’s character soon became a byword for such shady characters in real life). In the stage production, Trilby wore a felt hat with a pinch at the front and a narrow brim, and the term ‘A Trilby Hat’ simply caught on.
B.H.
